<p id="p0180">The standard base for a general study of electron-vibrational interactions is the adiabatic theory [
 <xref rid="bib53" ref-type="bibr">53</xref>, 
 <xref rid="bib65" ref-type="bibr">65</xref>, 
 <xref rid="bib66" ref-type="bibr">66</xref>, 
 <xref rid="bib67" ref-type="bibr">67</xref>], which uses the only universal small parameter of the molecule — the Born-Oppenheimer parameter 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M52" altimg="si42.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>κ</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mo>
    <msup>
     <mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
       <mrow>
        <mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mi>μ</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mo linebreak="badbreak">/</mo>
         <mrow>
          <mtext>M</mtext>
         </mrow>
        </mrow>
       </mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mrow>
        <mn>1</mn>
       </mrow>
       <mo linebreak="badbreak">/</mo>
       <mrow>
        <mn>4</mn>
       </mrow>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
    </msup>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, where 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M53" altimg="si43.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>μ</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the electron mass and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M54" altimg="si44.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mtext>M</mtext>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the typical mass of the nucleus.
</p>
